As an AI text model, I cannot directly generate a binary 3D file (like `.obj`, `.fbx`, or `.gltf`) that you can download and open in software like Blender or Unity.

However, I can provide you with **three different ways** to "render" a 3D house depending on your needs:

1.  **Code-Based Rendering**: A complete Python script using `Three.js` (via a browser) to generate and animate a 3D house instantly.
2.  **Text-to-3D Prompts**: Prompts you can copy and paste into AI image generators (like Midjourney, DALL-E 3) or 3D generation tools (like Tripo, CSM, or Meshy) to create the model.
3.  **ASCII Art**: A text-based wireframe representation.

---

### Option 1: Interactive 3D House (Python + Three.js)
You can run this code in any Python environment that supports `pywebgl` or simply save it as an `.html` file if you have the libraries installed. This creates a real-time, rotatable 3D house in your browser.

**Prerequisites:**
You need a Python environment with `pywebgl` installed, or you can save the code below as `house.html` and open it in a browser if you have the Three.js CDN linked.

Here is a standalone HTML/JS version you can save as `house.html` and open immediately in Chrome/Firefox:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>3D House Model</title>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; overflow: hidden; background-color: #87CEEB; }
        canvas { display: block; }
        #info { position: absolute; top: 10px; width: 100%; text-align: center; color: white; font-family: sans-serif; pointer-events: none; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="info">Left Click to Rotate | Right Click to Pan | Scroll to Zoom</div>
    <!-- Load Three.js from CDN -->
    <script type="importmap">
        {
            "imports": {
                "three": "https://unpkg.com/three@0.160.0/build/three.module.js",
                "three/addons/": "https://unpkg.com/three@0.160.0/examples/jsm/"
            }
        }
    </script>

    <script type="module">
        import * as THREE from 'three';
        import { OrbitControls } from 'three/addons/controls/OrbitControls.js';

        // 1. Scene Setup
        const scene = new THREE.Scene();
        scene.background = new THREE.Color(0x87CEEB); // Sky blue
        scene.fog = new THREE.Fog(0x87CEEB, 10, 50);

        const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(60, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
        camera.position.set(5, 5, 8);

        const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ antialias: true });
        renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        renderer.shadowMap.enabled = true;
        document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

        // 2. Lighting
        const ambientLight = new THREE.AmbientLight(0xffffff, 0.6);
        scene.add(ambientLight);

        const dirLight = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xffffff, 1);
        dirLight.position.set(10, 20, 10);
        dirLight.castShadow = true;
        dirLight.shadow.mapSize.width = 2048;
        dirLight.shadow.mapSize.height = 2048;
        scene.add(dirLight);

        // 3. Materials
        const wallMat = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0xeeeeee, roughness: 0.8 });
        const roofMat = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x8B4513, roughness: 0.9 });
        const windowMat = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x88ccff, emissive: 0x88ccff, emissiveIntensity: 0.5 });
        const doorMat = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x5c3a21 });
        const grassMat = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x4caf50 });

        // 4. Building the House
        const houseGroup = new THREE.Group();

        // Floor
        const floorGeo = new THREE.BoxGeometry(10, 1, 10);
        const floor = new THREE.Mesh(floorGeo, grassMat);
        floor.position.y = -0.5;
        floor.receiveShadow = true;
        houseGroup.add(floor);

        // Main Body
        const bodyGeo = new THREE.BoxGeometry(6, 4, 6);
        const body = new THREE.Mesh(bodyGeo, wallMat);
        body.position.y = 2;
        body.castShadow = true;
        body.receiveShadow = true;
        houseGroup.add(body);

        // Roof
        const roofGeo = new THREE.ConeGeometry(5, 2, 4);
        const roof = new THREE.Mesh(roofGeo, roofMat);
        roof.position.y = 5;
        roof.rotation.y = Math.PI / 4;
        roof.castShadow = true;
        houseGroup.add(roof);

        // Windows
        const winGeo = new THREE.BoxGeometry(1.5, 1.5, 0.2);
        const win1 = new THREE.Mesh(winGeo, windowMat);
        win1.position.set(1, 3, 2.6);
        houseGroup.add(win1);

        const win2 = new THREE.Mesh(winGeo, windowMat);
        win2.position.set(-1, 3, 2.6);
        houseGroup.add(win2);

        // Door
        const doorGeo = new THREE.BoxGeometry(1.5, 2.5, 0.2);
        const door = new THREE.Mesh(doorGeo, doorMat);
        door.position.set(0, 1.25, 2.6);
        houseGroup.add(door);

        scene.add(houseGroup);

        // 5. Controls
        const controls = new OrbitControls(camera, renderer.domElement);
        controls.enableDamping = true;
        controls.autoRotate = true;
        controls.autoRotateSpeed = 2.0;

        // 6. Animation Loop
        function animate() {
            requestAnimationFrame(animate);
            controls.update();
            renderer.render(scene, camera);
        }

        // Handle Resize
        window.addEventListener('resize', () => {
            camera.aspect = window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight;
            camera.updateProjectionMatrix();
            renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        });

        animate();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

**How to use this:**
1.  Copy the code above.
2.  Create a new file on your computer named `house.html`.
3.  Paste the code and save.
4.  Double-click `house.html` to open it in your web browser. You will see a rotating 3D house.

